                    <text>Some molecules are weak electrolytes and exist in a &lt;b&gt;reversible equilibrium&lt;/b&gt; between the starting molecule and its dissociated parts. For molecules that are weak electrolytes and act as acids (&lt;b&gt;proton donors&lt;/b&gt;), the ratio of the products of the dissociated parts and the parent molecule is a constant (&lt;b&gt;K&lt;/b&gt;) in neutral water for each separate molecular structure. 
